tax goods, process the dead before they reached core districts.
Practical mandate. Sound logistics.

Then came the Plague Mandate. Emergency directives authorized
rapid intake, forced quarantines, cremation powers, suspension of
lineage appeals. Temporary became permanent. No authority agreed on
rollback. The Last Bell Crisis saw three contradictory decrees
rung in one night: amnesty, lockdown, requisition. The city
calcified into mutually hostile systems.

This is the founding case. Every element of Three-Power Governance
was designed as a countermeasure to Shadowmere's failure:

The Compact Temples hold sanctuary law but cannot issue quarantine
orders -- preventing the deadlock that paralyzed Shadowmere's rites.

The Trade Syndics hold market authority but cannot conscript or
seize goods without Wall Command countersignature -- preventing the
requisition spiral that stripped Shadowmere's merchants.

Wall Command holds gate discipline but cannot extend emergency
powers beyond one lunar cycle without Syndic and Temple renewal --
preventing the permanent emergency that turned garrison into
occupation.

And above all: "No sealed warrant from a predecessor authority
shall bind a Kiess citizen." Because Shadowmere's five factions --
the Oathbound March executing obsolete orders, the Crimson
Household claiming bloodline, the Binder Collegium treating souls
as ledger entries, the Gallows Syndicate monetizing execution, the
Fen-Adapted Remnants proving ecology outlasts governance -- all
still invoke law. All still stamp, witness, and seal. All are
wrong.

Shadowmere is what happens when lawful systems become predatory
under emergency powers without sunset. Kiess reads that sentence
at every founding anniversary, carved into the Prism's eastern face.

Emergency powers without sunset are poison. We wrote that in
stone so we would not forget.
